<TITLE> Ex-NSI director arrested over Chittagong arms haul </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 3(bdnews24.com)Police arrested former director (security) of National Security Intelligence wing commander Shahabuddin from Dhaka in connection with sensational Chittagong arms haul case on late Saturday night. Based on the statement of NSI field officer Akbar Hossain, a team of Chittagong CID police arrested him in the capital's Green Road. The CID police superintendent of Chittagong zone, Mohammad Muslim, told bdnews24.com, "Shahabuddin is being brought to Chittagong from Dhaka." On completion of seven-day remand, Hossain gave a confessional statement at Chittagong Chief Metropolitan Magistrate's Court on Saturday afternoon. Akbar confessed that former NSI director Sahabuddin had ordered trucks to be rented for transport of arms after those had been offloaded at the jetty of Chittagong Urea Fertilizer Ltd. Akbar was remanded in custody first on April 19 and then on April 26. CID SP Muslim said, "Akbar gave the statement to the metropolitan magistrate from 4.30pm-9pm Saturday." "The statement will unfold many mysteries in the case," he said. Akbar was sent to Chittagong Central Jail after recording statement, said Muslim, also investigation officer of the case. Akbar was serving as field officer for NSI during the offloading of ten trucks of arms from a vessel at the restricted CUFL jetty on the night of April 1, 2004, investigators said. Truck owners Taslim Mallick and Habibur Rahman during questioning had also previously informed CID officials that Akbar had rented the trucks for transport of the arms, Muslim said. CID also questioned nine more navy officers who had been deputed to the Chittagong coastguards in 2004, bringing the total number of serving and former navy officers grilled in connection with the case over the past week to 29. bdnew
